BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:aixdesign-grain-cookbook-critical-ai-literacy-2026@artificialnouveau.gi
 thub.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T081731Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260831
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260901
SUMMARY:Deadline: AIxDESIGN: Grain\, Open Call for Critical AI Literacy Rec
 ipes
DESCRIPTION:Grain is a cookbook of critical and creative AI literacy exerci
 ses for educators across audiovisual and creative practice\, co-produced b
 y AIxDESIGN and the Netherlands Film Academy and led by Nadia Piet. The op
 en call collects 'recipes': tried-and-tested group exercises for the class
 room or workshop that get people thinking critically and making creatively
  with AI. Exercises can be hands-on or analog\, 15 minutes or a full day\,
  beginner or advanced\; the one hard requirement is that someone else can 
 read your recipe and run it themselves. Examples of what might fit: hands-
 on experiments with specific AI tools (image generators\, chatbots\, code 
 assistants\, video models)\; analog activities that reveal computational l
 ogic through embodied practice\; critical readings\, watchings\, or listen
 ings with structured discussion\; provocations\, games\, or role-plays tha
 t get at how AI sees\, thinks\, or makes\; and exercises that help people 
 figure out how they want to relate to AI in their own practice. WHAT YOU G
 ET: your recipe formatted and credited to you in the first edition of Grai
 n\, a print copy when it lands\, and an invite to the launch. Everything i
 s published under CC BY-SA 4.0 so the work can travel and you keep authors
 hip. FEE: this round offers a need-based fee for freelance and independent
  practitioners of EUR 150 per recipe\; if making the time would be hard wi
 thout it\, email hello@aixdesign.co with your proposal. After this round t
 he call stays open but the fee will not. LIVE SESSION: an optional 30-minu
 te live session on Wednesday 12 August 2026 at 16:00 CEST lets you bring a
  rough exercise and turn it into a recipe on the spot with the Grain Recip
 e Converter (online\, sign up at luma.com/84w148in). Submissions are open 
 until the end of August 2026\; Grain publishes March 2027. Submit via the 
 form\; questions to hello@aixdesign.co.\n\nOrganisation: AIxDESIGN\, co-pr
 oduced with the Netherlands Film Academy\nLocation: Remote/online\; open t
 o educators and practitioners based anywhere\nAward: Need-based fee of EUR
  150 per recipe for freelance and independent practitioners (email hello@a
 ixdesign.co if the time would be hard to make without it). Your recipe is 
 formatted and credited to you in the first edition of Grain\, plus a print
  copy and an invite to the launch. Published under CC BY-SA 4.0\; you keep
  authorship.\nDuration: One-off contribution\; Grain publishes March 2027\
 n\nMore: https://nadiapiet.notion.site/Open-Call-Grain-Cookbook-for-Critic
 al-AI-Literacy-38e37d003833804380acd027b6041d5a?utm_source=artificialnouve
 augrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://nadiapiet.notion.site/Open-Call-Grain-Cookbook-for-Critical-AI-
 Literacy-38e37d003833804380acd027b6041d5a?utm_source=artificialnouveaugran
 tdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Remote/online\; open to educators and practitioners based anywhere
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:aixdesign-kb-national-library-ai-exhibition-2026@artificialnouveau.gith
 ub.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T081731Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260831
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260901
SUMMARY:Deadline: AIxDESIGN x KB: Open Call for Sessions\, (Art)works and P
 erformances
DESCRIPTION:AIxDESIGN and the KB (Koninklijke Bibliotheek\, the National Li
 brary of the Netherlands) are building an exhibition and public programme 
 about AI\, made from the national collection\, at the KB in The Hague. Nad
 ia Piet is Creative Lead with the AIxDESIGN community\, co-presented with 
 the KB. The premise: long before neural nets\, libraries were the machines
  we built to organise human knowledge\, and the show uses the KB's collect
 ion to look at what AI is\, where it comes from\, and how it connects to t
 he older story of how we store\, sort\, and search what we know. Part of t
 he show lives in the KB Atelier\, with talks\, workshops\, and screenings 
 alongside\, intended as AI literacy you can wander into. WHAT THEY WANT: w
 ork that engages AI in some way (critical\, creative\, hands-on\, or playf
 ul)\; bonus if it also speaks to archives\, libraries\, or how we store an
 d sort knowledge\, though you do not need to touch the KB's collection to 
 take part. You may pitch to more than one track: (A) SOMETHING FOR THE OPE
 NING NIGHT\, a performance\, talk\, screening\, tour\, ritual\, booth\, ga
 me\, or other experience for the November 2026 opening\, fee EUR 1\,500 to
  2\,000\; (B) A SESSION IN THE EVENTS PROGRAMME\, a workshop or other sess
 ion once during the three-month run\, around 2.5 to 4 hours\, fee EUR 2\,0
 00 to 2\,500\; (C) AN (ART)WORK FOR THE EXHIBITION\, existing work in any 
 format (installation\, sculpture\, zine stand\, a corner of your own) stur
 dy enough for a public area with daily traffic\, honorarium EUR 200 to 400
  including licensing and production\; (D) SOMETHING ELSE ENTIRELY\, pitch 
 it anyway. WHO: artists\, designers\, researchers\, technologists\, perfor
 mers\, musicians\, archivists\, or educators working around AI\, data\, li
 braries\, or cultural heritage\; no finished idea or polished CV needed\, 
 just a clear\, specific pitch. You can be based anywhere and they especial
 ly welcome people outside the Netherlands\; the show is in-person in The H
 ague and the fee stays the same wherever you are coming from. HOW TO APPLY
 : send a short pitch through the form (which track\, your idea in a paragr
 aph or two\, roughly what it would need\, and a link to your work)\; takes
  about five minutes\, no full application required. Deadline: end of Augus
 t 2026. Questions to hello@aixdesign.co.\n\nOrganisation: AIxDESIGN\, co-p
 resented with the Koninklijke Bibliotheek (KB)\, National Library of the N
 etherlands\nLocation: KB\, The Hague\, Netherlands (in-person exhibition a
 nd programme)\; pitches welcome from people based anywhere\nAward: Fees by
  track: opening-night experience EUR 1\,500 to 2\,000\; a session in the e
 vents programme EUR 2\,000 to 2\,500\; an existing (art)work for the exhib
 ition EUR 200 to 400 honorarium (including licensing and production). The 
 fee stays the same wherever you are based.\nDuration: Exhibition runs Nove
 mber 2026 to February 2027\; opening event November 2026\n\nMore: https://
 nadiapiet.notion.site/Open-Call-AIxDESIGN-x-KB-Sessions-Art-works-More-38f
 37d0038338102b128c57cbeb16d2d?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_me
 dium=referral
URL:https://nadiapiet.notion.site/Open-Call-AIxDESIGN-x-KB-Sessions-Art-wor
 ks-More-38f37d0038338102b128c57cbeb16d2d?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrant
 desk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:KB\, The Hague\, Netherlands (in-person exhibition and programme)\
 ; pitches welcome from people based anywhere
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:govai-us-ai-policy-program-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T081731Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260705
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260706
SUMMARY:Deadline: GovAI U.S. AI Policy Program
DESCRIPTION:The GovAI U.S. AI Policy Program is a bipartisan\, part-time\, 
 12-week program designed to accelerate or launch careers in U.S. AI policy
 . Open to U.S. policy professionals across government and think tanks\, it
  builds a technically-informed understanding of the AI policy landscape th
 rough guided discussion sessions\, with an emphasis on general-purpose AI.
  Topics include how general-purpose AI systems are developed\; inputs to A
 I development such as energy\, chips\, and data centers\; AI's effects on 
 productivity\, scientific discovery\, and economic growth\; national secur
 ity and great power competition\; corporate self-governance\; AI regulatio
 n in other jurisdictions\; and federal and state AI regulatory proposals i
 n the U.S. Participants also have weekly opportunities to question world-l
 eading experts\; prior guest speakers have included White House OSTP staff
 ers\, former frontier-lab employees\, and people who helped draft U.S. sta
 te- and federal-level AI policy proposals. The program runs early Septembe
 r to early December 2026 (break for Thanksgiving week) with a roughly 5-ho
 ur weekly commitment: two hours of synchronous evening sessions (EST)\, he
 ld in-person at GovAI's D.C. office near DuPont Circle or remotely with ca
 meras on\, plus three hours of independent reading and podcasts from a fre
 e syllabus. To list completion on a resume\, participants must attend 9 of
  12 sessions\, write a short policy memo or op-ed\, and pass an interview-
 based exam. Eligible participants include executive and legislative branch
  staff (fellows\, interns\, detailees\, military personnel\, national labo
 ratory personnel) and think-tank policy researchers and affiliates\, acros
 s a range of seniority levels\, with preference for the D.C. metropolitan 
 area\; participants need not currently cover AI but should aspire to a car
 eer in U.S. tech or national security policy. Selection has two stages: an
  online application with six biographical questions\, a resume\, two verba
 l reasoning questions\, and an approximately 7-minute video\; followed by 
 a 30-minute interview in July\, with final decisions in early August.\n\nO
 rganisation: Centre for the Governance of AI (GovAI)\nLocation: Washington
 \, D.C.\, USA (hybrid\; remote participation available)\nAward: Free to pa
 rticipate\; in-person attendees provided dinner (value kept at or below US
 D 20 per session)\nDuration: 12-week part-time program\, early September t
 o early December 2026 (approximately 5 hours per week)\n\nMore: https://ww
 w.governance.ai/post/govai-u-s-ai-policy-program?utm_source=artificialnouv
 eaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.governance.ai/post/govai-u-s-ai-policy-program?utm_source=a
 rtificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Washington\, D.C.\, USA (hybrid\; remote participation available)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ford-foundation-technology-fellow-ai-philanthropy-2026@artificialnouvea
 u.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T081731Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260706
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260707
SUMMARY:Deadline: Technology Fellow: AI and Philanthropy
DESCRIPTION:The Ford Foundation seeks a two-year Technology Fellow for AI a
 nd Philanthropy\, an internally-facing role focused on cross-programmatic 
 learning and advisory support. Reporting to the Director\, Technology and 
 Society\, the AI Tech Fellow will support Foundation staff in building and
  adapting internal frameworks for evaluating AI use in ways that prioritiz
 e mission and strategy and address ethical\, sociotechnical\, and operatio
 nal considerations. Responsibilities include designing and curating hands-
 on trainings\, workshops\, and learning sessions to help staff build pract
 ical familiarity with AI tools and critically assess their value and effic
 acy\; creating accessible documentation and guides on mission-aligned AI e
 xperimentation\; curating sociotechnical conversations on how philanthropy
  and the nonprofit sector are experimenting with AI in ways that respect p
 rivacy\, safety\, and equity\; monitoring emerging global AI developments 
 and providing timely briefings to program teams\; conducting landscape res
 earch on AI initiatives in the philanthropy and social justice sectors\; a
 nd building relationships with AI researchers\, practitioners\, grantees a
 nd partners working on mission-enabling AI. The Technology Fellows Program
  is administered by Ford's Technology and Society Program and is designed 
 to increase sociotechnical capacity within the Foundation. Requirements in
 clude a minimum of 7 years working within public-interest\, government\, c
 ivil society\, or commercial technology sectors\; a baccalaureate degree o
 r equivalent experience\; demonstrated sociotechnical expertise in artific
 ial intelligence and related technologies including machine learning syste
 ms and generative AI and their societal implications\; and experience desi
 gning\, implementing or supporting AI applications and tools in a complex 
 global setting. Hybrid role based in New York (three days per week in offi
 ce). Not eligible for visa sponsorship\; candidates must be authorized to 
 work in the United States. Submit both a resume and a cover letter to be c
 onsidered.\n\nOrganisation: Ford Foundation\nLocation: New York\, New York
 \, USA\nAward: USD 166\,000 to 170\,000 annual salary\, plus comprehensive
  benefits and retirement contributions of up to 13%\nDuration: Two-year te
 rm-limited contract\n\nMore: https://fordfoundation.wd1.myworkdayjobs.com/
 en-US/FordFoundationCareerPage/details/Technology-Fellow--AI-and-Philanthr
 opy_R1294?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://fordfoundation.wd1.myworkdayjobs.com/en-US/FordFoundationCareer
 Page/details/Technology-Fellow--AI-and-Philanthropy_R1294?utm_source=artif
 icialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:New York\, New York\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:genesis-mission-ai-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T081731Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260731
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260801
SUMMARY:Deadline: Genesis Mission AI Fellowship 2026
DESCRIPTION:The Horizon Institute for Public Service\, Renaissance Philanth
 ropy\, SeedAI\, and Fulcrum Science are partnering to launch a fellowship 
 that embeds technical AI talent across the US Department of Energy nationa
 l labs to advance the goals of the Genesis Mission\, DOE's flagship scienc
 e and technology initiative launched in late 2025. The Genesis Mission ide
 ntifies 26 national science and technology challenges critical to US leade
 rship and envisions a national platform connecting supercomputers\, experi
 mental facilities\, AI systems\, and unique datasets\, with DOE's 17 natio
 nal labs playing a key role. Genesis Mission AI Fellows are forward deploy
 ed to DOE national labs to bring frontier AI expertise to high-priority sc
 ientific challenges. As core members of the technical staff on a Genesis M
 ission project\, fellows work alongside national lab scientists and partne
 rs and apply AI to national priorities\, from building cutting-edge models
  of plasma dynamics in pursuit of controlled fusion to advancing state-of-
 the-art models for foundational materials discovery. Initial national lab 
 partners include Idaho National Laboratory\, Brookhaven National Laborator
 y\, and the Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory\; additional partners may 
 be announced later. COMPENSATION/DURATION: 9-12 months starting fall 2026\
 , with a prorated total annual compensation of USD 200\,000\; fellows are 
 expected to travel to their national lab site at least once a quarter but 
 may work on-site if they prefer. ELIGIBILITY: competitive applicants shoul
 d have at least 2 years of industry experience building AI models or agent
 s (those with industry experience building AI applications or data infrast
 ructure will also be considered)\; scientific domain expertise is not requ
 ired\, but any placement will involve some training and study in a specifi
 c scientific discipline or energy topic\, supported by expert colleagues a
 t the host institution. All fellows must be eligible to work in the United
  States for the duration of the placement\; US employment visas cannot be 
 sponsored\, but US permanent residents (green card holders) are eligible. 
 APPLICATION: initial form requires a CV or resume (max 2 pages) and short-
 answer questions on motivations and experiences (max 200 words)\; successf
 ul applicants complete interviews through partner organizations and nation
 al labs\, and selected fellows are matched to partner labs by scientific d
 omain and availability. The review uses evidence-based best practices incl
 uding blind grading of application materials. TIMELINE: application deadli
 ne 31 July 2026\; final fellow selection August-September 2026\; expected 
 start fall 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Horizon Institute for Public Service (wi
 th Renaissance Philanthropy\, SeedAI\, and Fulcrum Science)\nLocation: Uni
 ted States. Fellows are forward deployed to US Department of Energy nation
 al labs (initial partners: Idaho National Laboratory\, Brookhaven National
  Laboratory\, Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory). Remote or in-person\; 
 on-site travel at least once a quarter. Must be eligible to work in the US
  (no visa sponsorship\; US green card holders eligible).\nAward: Prorated 
 total annual compensation of USD 200\,000.\nDuration: 9-12 months\, starti
 ng fall 2026.\n\nMore: https://horizonpublicservice.org/announcing-the-gen
 esis-mission-ai-fellowship/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medi
 um=referral
URL:https://horizonpublicservice.org/announcing-the-genesis-mission-ai-fell
 owship/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:United States. Fellows are forward deployed to US Department of En
 ergy national labs (initial partners: Idaho National Laboratory\, Brookhav
 en National Laboratory\, Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory). Remote or i
 n-person\; on-site travel at least once a quarter. Must be eligible to wor
 k in the US (no visa sponsorship\; US green card holders eligible).
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:openai-economic-research-exchange-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T081731Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260705
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260706
SUMMARY:Deadline: OpenAI Economic Research Exchange 2026
DESCRIPTION:The OpenAI Economic Research Exchange is a new program supporti
 ng high-impact external research on the economic effects of AI. Through th
 e Exchange\, selected researchers conduct work via structured\, project-ba
 sed collaborations with OpenAI Economic Research\, with the goal of produc
 ing credible\, independent evidence on how AI is affecting workers\, firms
 \, institutions\, and the broader economy. OpenAI is seeking projects that
  address important questions about the economic impacts of AI\; proposals 
 should explain how carefully governed\, privacy-protected use of OpenAI to
 ols and datasets can help answer these questions\, extending beyond what t
 raditional datasets alone allow\, while maintaining clear safeguards for u
 ser privacy and responsible data use. Core questions include labor market 
 effects (moving beyond AI exposure to measure which occupations are likely
  to see augmentation\, displacement\, new task creation\, or employment gr
 owth as model capabilities improve) and measuring economic value (willingn
 ess to pay\, revealed value\, task-level time savings\, avoided costs\, qu
 ality-adjusted output\, and durable productivity gains). Selected research
 ers undertake carefully scoped projects with defined milestones\, data gov
 ernance\, and review processes. WHO SHOULD APPLY: researchers with strong 
 empirical skills and relevant expertise in applied causal inference\, meas
 urement\, labor economics\, productivity\, firms\, education\, entrepreneu
 rship\, public finance\, regional economics\, development\, inequality\, o
 r related fields. EVALUATION: proposals are assessed on methodological rig
 or\, feasibility\, fit with Exchange priorities\, clear milestones\, and t
 he potential to contribute credible external evidence on AI's economic imp
 acts. The Exchange builds on OpenAI's broader measurement efforts\, includ
 ing OpenAI Signals. For more information see the Request for Proposals\, o
 r contact econresearch@openai.com. Applications close 5 July 2026\; select
 ed researchers will be notified by 31 July 2026.\n\nOrganisation: OpenAI\n
 Location: Remote / global. Structured\, project-based research collaborati
 ons with OpenAI Economic Research. No location restriction stated.\nAward:
  USD 25\,000 project grant plus a USD 7\,500 monthly stipend per selected 
 researcher.\nDuration: Carefully scoped projects with defined milestones. 
 OpenAI supports a portfolio across time horizons: short-term projects (2-6
  months) using existing approved data\, and medium-term studies (6-12 mont
 hs) that track outcomes over time or test specific interventions.\n\nMore:
  https://openai.com/index/economic-research-exchange-request-for-proposals
 /?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://openai.com/index/economic-research-exchange-request-for-proposa
 ls/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Remote / global. Structured\, project-based research collaboration
 s with OpenAI Economic Research. No location restriction stated.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:utah-oaip-ai-research-fellow-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T081731Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260624
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260625
SUMMARY:Deadline: AI Research Fellow / Senior AI Policy Researcher (Utah Of
 fice of AI Policy)
DESCRIPTION:The Utah Department of Commerce\, Office of Artificial Intellig
 ence Policy\, is seeking an AI Research Fellow to help drive technical\, s
 cientific\, and policy research for Utah's AI Learning Lab. This is an app
 lied research and policy-translation role whose work should directly infor
 m regulatory decisions\, legislative recommendations\, regulatory mitigati
 on agreements\, and stakeholder strategy. The role is technical and relies
  heavily on statistical\, machine learning\, computer science\, and empiri
 cal research skills\, while also requiring strong judgment\, clear writing
 \, and the ability to operate in a small multidisciplinary team alongside 
 colleagues with policy\, business\, regulatory\, and legal expertise. The 
 Office of Artificial Intelligence Policy was created in May 2024 to system
 atically develop sensible AI policy across major impact areas such as heal
 thcare\, education\, finance\, transportation\, and consumer technology. C
 entral to the Office is the AI Learning Lab\, where industry experts\, aca
 demics\, regulators\, and policymakers work toward appropriate regulatory 
 responses to emerging AI applications\; the Office also has authority to c
 reate regulatory mitigation agreements that let responsible AI businesses 
 test products in Utah under structured conditions while the state gathers 
 evidence. KEY RESPONSIBILITIES: independently scope and execute research p
 rojects on emerging AI policy questions (defining the question\, identifyi
 ng technical and empirical evidence\, interviewing experts\, evaluating tr
 adeoffs\, and producing written recommendations)\; research the technical 
 aspects\, capabilities\, limitations\, and societal impacts of AI technolo
 gies\; evaluate evidence and forecasts on the impact of human-AI interacti
 ons on health\, economic activity\, education\, consumer welfare\, and pub
 lic institutions\; draft executive policy memos\, legislative briefings\, 
 technical explainers\, risk assessments\, and regulatory mitigation analys
 es\; interface with business leaders\, technologists\, researchers\, regul
 ators\, legislators\, and lawyers\; and advise on the development of regul
 atory and legal standards. MINIMUM QUALIFICATIONS: deep technical knowledg
 e of statistical methods\, machine learning\, and AI systems\; strong abil
 ity to translate technical and empirical evidence into practical policy op
 tions for nontechnical decision-makers\; familiarity with human-subject re
 search\, qualitative and quantitative methods\, medical or health sciences
 \, social sciences\, human-computer interaction\, or related empirical fie
 lds\; excellent problem-solving\, reliability\, and independent judgment\;
  and strong technical communication across policy\, legal\, regulatory\, b
 usiness\, and technical audiences. PREFERRED: experience implementing\, ev
 aluating\, or deploying AI systems (business\, healthcare\, government\, o
 r other applied settings)\; expertise in public policy\, law\, regulatory 
 design\, or government decision-making\; ability to evaluate technical cla
 ims\, research methods\, and evidence quality\; specific healthcare experi
 ence\; and experience supporting AI deployment in regulated environments. 
 A criminal history check is required. Recruiter: Tehra Gorski\, tgorski@ut
 ah.gov\, 801-530-6030. Application deadline 24 June 2026.\n\nOrganisation:
  Utah Department of Commerce\, Office of Artificial Intelligence Policy\nL
 ocation: Salt Lake City\, Utah\, United States. Hybrid telework may be ava
 ilable but regular in-person work is required\, and in-state work rules re
 quire all work to be performed while physically within Utah. No visa spons
 orship.\nAward: Salary: USD 33.13 to 54.01 hourly wage. Full-time\, time-l
 imited position. Job classification Research Consultant III (#16048)\; may
  underfill as Research Consultant II (#16058) with a reduced salary range.
 \nDuration: Full-time\, time-limited (Schedule Code TL).\n\nMore: https://
 utdgohcm.csod.com/ux/ats/careersite/4/home/requisition/1419?c=utdgohcm&utm
 _source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://utdgohcm.csod.com/ux/ats/careersite/4/home/requisition/1419?c=u
 tdgohcm&utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Salt Lake City\, Utah\, United States. Hybrid telework may be avai
 lable but regular in-person work is required\, and in-state work rules req
 uire all work to be performed while physically within Utah. No visa sponso
 rship.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:tech-to-the-rescue-ai-impact-scaling-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T081731Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260630
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260701
SUMMARY:Deadline: AI Impact Scaling Program 2026 (Tech To The Rescue)
DESCRIPTION:The AI Impact Scaling Program from Tech To The Rescue helps non
 profits and social impact organizations use AI to expand the reach and eff
 ectiveness of interventions that already demonstrate measurable results. T
 he focus is scaling proven impact\, not proving it. Selected organizations
  get access to an ecosystem designed to turn proven programs into scalable
  AI-powered solutions\, including: a matched pro bono technology partner f
 rom a network of 2\,000+ software companies and AI experts\; scaling strat
 egy support and a tailored AI roadmap\; specialized guidance on responsibl
 e AI\, cybersecurity\, and data governance\; access to mentors\, infrastru
 cture credits\, and technical resources\; and visibility with funders and 
 investors through a global Demo Day. The program estimates participating o
 rganizations receive between USD 150\,000 and USD 330\,000 worth of servic
 es at no cost. WHO SHOULD APPLY: organizations with a proven intervention\
 , real users\, measurable outcomes\, and clear potential to scale\; NGOs a
 nd social impact organizations from around the world\; teams able to dedic
 ate a project lead for at least five hours per week over the 12-month prog
 ram. You do not need to have an AI solution already built\; the program he
 lps identify where AI can accelerate impact and then build the solution al
 ongside experienced technology partners. Application deadline 30 June 2026
 .\n\nOrganisation: Tech To The Rescue\nLocation: NGOs and social impact or
 ganizations from around the world. Requires a project lead able to commit 
 at least 5 hours per week over the 12-month program.\nAward: No-cost progr
 am. Participating organizations are estimated to receive between USD 150\,
 000 and USD 330\,000 worth of services at no cost\, including a matched pr
 o bono technology partner\, scaling strategy support\, a tailored AI roadm
 ap\, responsible-AI/cybersecurity/data-governance guidance\, mentors\, inf
 rastructure credits\, technical resources\, and visibility with funders an
 d investors via a global Demo Day.\nDuration: 12-month program.\n\nMore: h
 ttps://techtotherescue.org/ai-impact-scaling-program?utm_source=artificial
 nouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://techtotherescue.org/ai-impact-scaling-program?utm_source=artifi
 cialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:NGOs and social impact organizations from around the world. Requir
 es a project lead able to commit at least 5 hours per week over the 12-mon
 th program.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:scaling-ai-safety-multi-agent-world-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260709T081731Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260808
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260809
SUMMARY:Deadline: Scaling AI Safety for a Multi-Agent World (Joint Funding 
 Call)
DESCRIPTION:A joint philanthropic funding call by Schmidt Sciences\, Google
  DeepMind\, ARIA\, the Cooperative AI Foundation and Google.org to catalys
 e the foundational scientific research needed to understand\, evaluate and
  control risks emerging from large-scale ecosystems of interacting AI agen
 ts deployed by multiple actors (multi-principal\, multi-agent settings). T
 he call argues that focusing only on the safety and alignment of individua
 l models is insufficient\, and seeks system-level approaches. RESEARCH AGE
 NDA (four clusters): (1) Sandboxes and Testbeds\, realistic\, reproducible
  multi-agent environments for studying populations of frontier-model agent
 s\; (2) The Science of Agent Networks\, how collective capabilities emerge
  and scale\, how networks fail\, and how dangerous population-level proper
 ties can be detected\; (3) Strengthening Agent Infrastructure\, evaluating
  and stress-testing primitives such as identity\, verifiability\, reputati
 on\, communication and commitment\; (4) Multi-Agent Oversight and Control\
 , detection\, attribution\, security and intervention methods to keep depl
 oyed agent populations safe at scale. Proposals may target one cluster or 
 span several\, with priority on depth over breadth and on realistic sandbo
 xes and testbeds. OUT OF SCOPE: single-agent safety\, capability advanceme
 nt without a clear safety motivation\, toy systems\, naive application of 
 pre-existing solutions\, commercial product development\, and purely conce
 ptual/policy work. ELIGIBILITY: individual researchers\, research teams\, 
 research institutions and multi-institution collaborations across universi
 ties\, national laboratories\, institutes and nonprofit research organisat
 ions\; open globally. Informational webinars on 30 June and 23 July 2026\;
  notification of decisions in autumn 2026. Proposals due 8 August 2026 by 
 11:59pm Anywhere on Earth. Contact: multiagentsafety@schmidtsciences.org. 
 Apply at https://schmidtsciences.smapply.io/prog/scaling_ai_safety_for_a_m
 ulti_agent_world/.\n\nOrganisation: Schmidt Sciences\, Google DeepMind\, t
 he Advanced Research & Invention Agency (ARIA)\, the Cooperative AI Founda
 tion\, and Google.org\nLocation: Global\; open worldwide\, with collaborat
 ions across geographic boundaries encouraged.\nAward: Two funding tiers (a
 pplicants may apply to either or both)\, projects 1 to 2 years. Tier 1: up
  to USD 300\,000 for exploratory research\, pilot studies\, or focused tec
 hnical investigations. Tier 2: USD 300\,000 to USD 1\,000\,000 for more am
 bitious or collaborative projects. For projects funded by Schmidt Sciences
 \, indirect costs must be at or below 10%. No application fee.\nDuration: 
 1 to 2 years\n\nMore: https://schmidtsciences.smapply.io/prog/scaling_ai_s
 afety_for_a_multi_agent_world/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_m
 edium=referral
URL:https://schmidtsciences.smapply.io/prog/scaling_ai_safety_for_a_multi_a
 gent_world/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Global\; open worldwide\, with collaborations across geographic bo
 undaries encouraged.
